1
00:00:05,756 --> 00:00:08,842
[ominous music pulsing]

2
00:00:23,273 --> 00:00:25,192
[knocking on door]

3
00:00:25,275 --> 00:00:27,069
[pulsing subsides]

4
00:00:27,152 --> 00:00:29,947
[birds singing outside]

5
00:00:31,865 --> 00:00:33,158
-Thank you.
-[Saul] Mm.

6
00:00:34,368 --> 00:00:36,370
[somber instrumental music playing]

7
00:00:38,580 --> 00:00:39,498
[lighter clicks]

8
00:00:55,681 --> 00:00:57,516
The blinking stars.

9
00:00:57,599 --> 00:00:58,600
Yep.

10
00:00:59,685 --> 00:01:00,811
Do you have a theory?

11
00:01:01,728 --> 00:01:03,480
I do. [exhales]

12
00:01:03,564 --> 00:01:04,731
It's bullshit.

13
00:01:05,315 --> 00:01:06,233
Bullshit?

14
00:01:06,316 --> 00:01:07,651
It never happened.

15
00:01:08,151 --> 00:01:11,405
How can that be? The world saw it happen.

16
00:01:11,488 --> 00:01:14,449
Sure, everyone on Earth.
But you know who <i>didn't </i>see it?

17
00:01:14,533 --> 00:01:18,120
Webb, Hubble, CHEOPS.

18
00:01:18,829 --> 00:01:20,581
None of the satellites saw it.
You know why?

19
00:01:21,248 --> 00:01:23,709
-Why?
-Because it never happened.

20
00:01:23,792 --> 00:01:25,127
It was a deepfake.

21
00:01:26,420 --> 00:01:28,046
Interesting theory.

22
00:01:28,130 --> 00:01:30,215
Who pulled this deepfake?

23
00:01:30,299 --> 00:01:32,009
That's as far as I got.

24
00:01:36,722 --> 00:01:38,807
[indistinct chatter]

25
00:01:42,436 --> 00:01:43,270
[Auggie sighs]

26
00:01:44,646 --> 00:01:47,816
Whatever you decide,
that's the right thing to do.

27
00:01:53,530 --> 00:01:55,741
-Love you, Auggie.
-[Auggie] Love you more.

28
00:01:58,785 --> 00:01:59,786
[sighs]

29
00:02:02,748 --> 00:02:05,042
-[woman 1] Maybe.
-[Auggie] Morning.

30
00:02:05,125 --> 00:02:07,502
[indistinct, excited chatter]

31
00:02:08,295 --> 00:02:11,548
We've seen shifts in apparent magnitude
of single stars, but never this.

32
00:02:11,632 --> 00:02:13,925
What about some kind
of atmospheric distortion?

33
00:02:14,009 --> 00:02:15,093
Interstellar dust?

34
00:02:15,177 --> 00:02:17,220
Then you'd expect variation
between lines of sight.

35
00:02:17,304 --> 00:02:20,057
[man 1] Did you see the flickering stars
last night, Dr. Salazar?

36
00:02:20,140 --> 00:02:21,016
Um…

37
00:02:21,099 --> 00:02:22,184
[espresso machine whirring]

38
00:02:22,267 --> 00:02:23,268
Yeah.

39
00:02:23,769 --> 00:02:25,937
-[machine beeping]
-Any theories?

40
00:02:28,190 --> 00:02:29,024
No.

41
00:02:29,524 --> 00:02:31,693
-[indistinct chatter]
-[man 2] Good morning, Doctor.

42
00:02:31,777 --> 00:02:33,070
-Morning.
-[man 2] Morning.

43
00:02:36,156 --> 00:02:38,742
-Are you ready?
-[energy thrumming]

44
00:02:38,825 --> 00:02:40,452
Let's see what happens.

45
00:02:41,828 --> 00:02:45,290
[suspenseful instrumental music playing]

46
00:02:46,291 --> 00:02:47,501
[Auggie inhales sharply]

47
00:02:49,378 --> 00:02:51,380
[machinery whirring]

48
00:02:58,845 --> 00:03:01,264
[woman 2 on PA] <i>Nanofiber array is stable.</i>

49
00:03:01,348 --> 00:03:03,934
<i>The synthetic diamond is secured.</i>

50
00:03:04,017 --> 00:03:05,769
Just briefly, Dr. Salazar,

51
00:03:05,852 --> 00:03:11,608
I'm sure I speak for all of us when I say…
we thought you were crazy seven years ago.

52
00:03:11,692 --> 00:03:13,110
[group chuckles]

53
00:03:13,193 --> 00:03:17,614
But your extraordinary vision
has got us to this moment.

54
00:03:20,325 --> 00:03:22,035
-So, thank you.
-[Auggie sighs]

55
00:03:22,119 --> 00:03:24,037
It's been a privilege, really.

56
00:03:24,621 --> 00:03:26,498
[hesitates] Whenever you're ready.

57
00:03:26,581 --> 00:03:29,334
[Auggie takes a deep breath] Go ahead.

58
00:03:29,418 --> 00:03:31,002
-[typing]
-[Auggie exhales]

59
00:03:31,503 --> 00:03:33,630
[woman 2 on PA] <i>Raising the diamond.</i>

60
00:03:33,714 --> 00:03:35,882
<i>Nanofiber lattice is active.</i>

61
00:03:35,966 --> 00:03:37,968
[machinery humming]

62
00:03:47,394 --> 00:03:49,104
[high-pitched whirring]

63
00:03:52,566 --> 00:03:54,526
[suspenseful music building]

64
00:03:56,570 --> 00:03:57,821
[faint slicing]

65
00:04:15,005 --> 00:04:17,299
[suspenseful music swells]

66
00:04:20,594 --> 00:04:22,596
[onlookers applauding]

67
00:04:22,679 --> 00:04:24,598
[energy crackling]

68
00:04:28,852 --> 00:04:29,853
[Auggie gasps]

69
00:04:31,396 --> 00:04:33,648
[man 3] You did it.
You made history, Auggie.

70
00:04:33,732 --> 00:04:36,485
-[group cheering]
-[woman 3] Well done!

71
00:04:36,568 --> 00:04:37,986
We have to shut it down.

72
00:04:39,863 --> 00:04:40,864
Shut it down!

73
00:04:42,199 --> 00:04:46,119
I'm Chief Scientific Officer,
and I'm ordering you to shut it down.

74
00:04:47,204 --> 00:04:48,330
Development stops.

75
00:04:48,413 --> 00:04:50,332
[breathing shakily]

76
00:04:51,166 --> 00:04:52,417
[softly] This is over.

77
00:04:56,171 --> 00:04:58,173
[energy continues crackling]

78
00:05:05,430 --> 00:05:08,225
[thrumming intensifies]

79
00:05:18,443 --> 00:05:20,529
[thrumming subsides]

80
00:05:20,612 --> 00:05:22,614
[birds singing]

81
00:05:31,081 --> 00:05:31,998
I'd keep moving.

82
00:05:33,291 --> 00:05:34,793
Your colleagues will be coming soon.

83
00:05:44,261 --> 00:05:45,136
Who are you?

84
00:05:48,348 --> 00:05:49,683
Maybe I can help you.

85
00:05:50,809 --> 00:05:52,185
Maybe you can help me.

86
00:05:53,103 --> 00:05:55,313
I don't think you can help me, Officer.

87
00:05:55,814 --> 00:05:59,734
Maybe not, but don't you wanna know
why the stars flickered for you?

88
00:06:00,861 --> 00:06:02,696
[menacing music pulsing]

89
00:06:04,364 --> 00:06:06,908
[futuristic piano theme playing]

90
00:06:14,875 --> 00:06:16,793
-[theme song fades]
-[static crackling]

91
00:06:16,877 --> 00:06:19,754
[man speaking Mandarin over radio]

92
00:06:21,464 --> 00:06:26,511
<i>We extend our best wishes to you,
inhabitants of another world.</i>

93
00:06:26,595 --> 00:06:33,059
<i>We hope to establish contact
with other civilized societies.</i>

94
00:06:33,143 --> 00:06:35,729
<i>We look forward to working with you</i>

95
00:06:35,812 --> 00:06:39,232
<i>to build a better life
in this vast universe.</i>

96
00:06:39,566 --> 00:06:44,070
[man] <i>We extend our best wishes to you,
inhabitants of another world.</i>

97
00:06:46,281 --> 00:06:49,409
How long have we been
transmitting our message?

98
00:06:49,492 --> 00:06:50,952
A few years.

99
00:06:51,161 --> 00:06:53,079
And the Americans? The Russians?

100
00:06:53,163 --> 00:06:54,372
Longer than that.

101
00:06:58,335 --> 00:07:00,462
It's the Fermi Paradox.

102
00:07:04,507 --> 00:07:10,347
It comes from a question that Enrico Fermi
asked his colleagues at Los Alamos.

103
00:07:11,348 --> 00:07:14,476
There are a hundred billion
stars in our galaxy.

104
00:07:14,559 --> 00:07:18,104
Many of these stars
must have planets similar to our own.

105
00:07:18,188 --> 00:07:22,609
And many of these planets
must have developed intelligent life.

106
00:07:25,111 --> 00:07:26,863
So where is everybody?

107
00:07:28,865 --> 00:07:32,035
Maybe there's no one out there.

108
00:07:32,118 --> 00:07:34,996
Our signal is too weak.

109
00:07:35,080 --> 00:07:37,707
25 megawatts is too weak?

110
00:07:37,958 --> 00:07:42,295
It's one of the most powerful
transmitters on the planet.

111
00:07:44,089 --> 00:07:45,465
Nobody will hear it.

112
00:07:50,428 --> 00:07:54,683
I need to contact the scientist
who wrote this article. Can you do that?

113
00:07:54,933 --> 00:07:56,017
[Yang Weining] Where is he?

114
00:07:56,476 --> 00:07:57,560
California.

115
00:07:59,020 --> 00:08:01,231
You want me to contact an American?

116
00:08:01,314 --> 00:08:03,900
If they find out they will question us.

117
00:08:04,275 --> 00:08:07,237
Then don't tell them about it.

118
00:08:09,864 --> 00:08:11,950
[static pulsating]

119
00:08:16,287 --> 00:08:17,956
[tapping on console]

120
00:08:20,375 --> 00:08:23,211
Any messages from outer space?

121
00:08:24,504 --> 00:08:25,922
I don't know how you do it.

122
00:08:26,006 --> 00:08:30,677
It's like listening
to the ocean for eight hours.

123
00:08:30,760 --> 00:08:34,723
I work out problems while I'm listening.

124
00:08:34,806 --> 00:08:35,724
[scoffs]

125
00:08:36,725 --> 00:08:37,726
Hmm.

126
00:08:37,809 --> 00:08:39,602
What's this?

127
00:08:40,687 --> 00:08:42,647
[quietly] Our secret?

128
00:08:43,773 --> 00:08:46,568
[in English] Dr. Peterson. California.

129
00:08:56,953 --> 00:08:58,038
[Yang Weining sighs]

130
00:09:01,1000 --> 00:09:03,585
EARTH

131
00:09:04,711 --> 00:09:08,298
[in Mandarin] On June 12th last year,
Dr. Peterson's team in California

132
00:09:08,381 --> 00:09:11,968
observed strong bursts

133
00:09:13,094 --> 00:09:16,598
of electromagnetic radiation from Jupiter.

134
00:09:16,681 --> 00:09:17,891
JUPITER

135
00:09:17,974 --> 00:09:21,770
On the same day,
we detected an intense radio burst.

136
00:09:23,354 --> 00:09:27,609
So we detected the same thing as America?

137
00:09:27,817 --> 00:09:32,947
No. Our recordings picked up the burst
13 minutes after Mt. Wilson.

138
00:09:34,032 --> 00:09:37,285
And not from Jupiter.

139
00:09:37,452 --> 00:09:38,495
From the Sun.

140
00:09:40,622 --> 00:09:44,667
SUN

141
00:09:50,590 --> 00:09:54,719
From Jupiter to the Earth,
it took 38 minutes.

142
00:09:55,553 --> 00:09:59,474
From Jupiter to the Sun,
it took 43 minutes.

143
00:09:59,557 --> 00:10:01,518
From the Sun to the Earth,

144
00:10:01,976 --> 00:10:03,978
8 minutes.

145
00:10:11,027 --> 00:10:18,034
43 plus 8 equals 51.
A difference of 13 minutes.

146
00:10:20,537 --> 00:10:23,790
I simplified the math for you.

147
00:10:25,708 --> 00:10:29,087
The Sun reflected
the radio waves from Jupiter?

148
00:10:29,170 --> 00:10:32,757
Not just reflected. It <i>amplified </i>them.

149
00:10:32,841 --> 00:10:37,595
The signal from the Sun was millions of
times stronger than the one from Jupiter.

150
00:10:37,679 --> 00:10:41,891
So we can use the Sun as a super-antenna?

151
00:10:41,975 --> 00:10:44,644
By aiming our signal at the Sun?

152
00:10:44,727 --> 00:10:45,728
Exactly.

153
00:10:46,271 --> 00:10:51,276
"We extend our best wishes to you,
inhabitants of another world."

154
00:10:52,402 --> 00:10:54,904
Ye Wenjie. This is genius.

155
00:10:54,988 --> 00:10:58,158
It could take us
many years to get a reply,

156
00:10:58,241 --> 00:11:05,248
but imagine China leading the world
in interstellar communication.

157
00:11:06,666 --> 00:11:08,751
I want to take it to Commissar Lei.

158
00:11:09,419 --> 00:11:10,628
[Yang Weining sighs]

159
00:11:11,880 --> 00:11:14,007
Yes. We should.

160
00:11:26,186 --> 00:11:29,480
This is a radical idea, Comrade Yang.

161
00:11:29,564 --> 00:11:32,442
Yes.
I've been working on it for some time.

162
00:11:32,525 --> 00:11:36,779
It could take many years
to get a response, but…

163
00:11:36,863 --> 00:11:37,780
Enter.

164
00:11:41,993 --> 00:11:43,244
I want her to verify your work.

165
00:11:47,332 --> 00:11:51,878
Comrade Yang has devised a way to use
the Sun to amplify our transmission.

166
00:11:54,297 --> 00:11:56,966
His numbers are compelling.

167
00:11:59,677 --> 00:12:02,305
You believe his calculations
to be correct?

168
00:12:06,267 --> 00:12:07,894
[quietly] They are correct.

169
00:12:10,104 --> 00:12:12,565
[Lei Zhicheng] You want to aim
a super-powerful radio beam at the Sun.

170
00:12:12,815 --> 00:12:14,150
At the Red Sun?

171
00:12:14,234 --> 00:12:17,028
Have you thought about the
political symbolism of such an experiment?

172
00:12:17,111 --> 00:12:18,404
[Yang Weining] Well. Commissar, I…

173
00:12:18,488 --> 00:12:23,493
[Lei Zhicheng] Who is the Red Sun
in the heart of the People?

174
00:12:25,245 --> 00:12:27,163
This is very disappointing from you,
Comrade Yang.

175
00:12:27,247 --> 00:12:29,165
And I would think, Comrade Ye Wenjie,

176
00:12:29,249 --> 00:12:31,167
that as the daughter of a class enemy

177
00:12:31,251 --> 00:12:32,835
you would have warned him

178
00:12:32,919 --> 00:12:34,462
how dangerous his ideas were.

179
00:12:34,545 --> 00:12:37,340
[Yang Weining] Sir.
Imagine our great Red Sun, our Chairman,

180
00:12:37,423 --> 00:12:39,425
amplifying the words of the People,
a hundred millionfold.

181
00:12:39,968 --> 00:12:42,095
Absolutely not. I forbid it.

182
00:12:42,178 --> 00:12:44,681
This could get us all executed.

183
00:12:44,764 --> 00:12:48,893
-[Lei Zhicheng lecturing indistinctly]
-[somber instrumental music playing]

184
00:12:54,983 --> 00:12:57,694
[somber music fades slowly]

185
00:12:58,111 --> 00:12:59,988
Test transmission in sixty seconds.

186
00:13:04,409 --> 00:13:07,370
[fly buzzing]

187
00:13:14,377 --> 00:13:16,212
[Ye Wenjie breathing shakily]

188
00:13:18,756 --> 00:13:20,008
[buttons clacking]

189
00:13:20,091 --> 00:13:21,718
[tense music playing]

190
00:13:21,801 --> 00:13:24,470
[resolute instrumental music playing]

191
00:13:38,568 --> 00:13:40,570
[satellite dish groaning]

192
00:13:47,410 --> 00:13:49,412
[engineer]
Test transmission in thirty seconds.

193
00:14:05,678 --> 00:14:07,805
[fly buzzing]

194
00:14:14,062 --> 00:14:16,773
Test transmission in ten.

195
00:14:17,023 --> 00:14:17,857
Nine.

196
00:14:17,940 --> 00:14:18,775
Eight.

197
00:14:18,983 --> 00:14:19,859
Seven.

198
00:14:19,942 --> 00:14:20,777
Six.

199
00:14:20,943 --> 00:14:21,819
Five.

200
00:14:21,903 --> 00:14:22,737
Four.

201
00:14:22,820 --> 00:14:23,654
Three.

202
00:14:23,905 --> 00:14:24,739
Two.

203
00:14:24,822 --> 00:14:25,656
One.

204
00:14:25,740 --> 00:14:26,949
Begin test transmission.

205
00:14:30,411 --> 00:14:32,413
[music building]

206
00:14:36,459 --> 00:14:37,627
[loud thud]

207
00:14:37,710 --> 00:14:39,796
-[fly buzzing]
-[chuckles]

208
00:14:42,465 --> 00:14:44,300
[engineer] Message sent.

209
00:14:44,384 --> 00:14:46,177
Test transmission complete.

210
00:14:47,178 --> 00:14:50,515
[dramatic orchestral music playing]

211
00:15:07,073 --> 00:15:09,075
[birds calling]

212
00:15:12,829 --> 00:15:14,872
[in English] What do you know
about this man?

213
00:15:18,334 --> 00:15:20,044
[Auggie] He was at Vera's funeral.

214
00:15:20,128 --> 00:15:21,587
Mike Evans.

215
00:15:21,671 --> 00:15:25,550
Owns Evans Energy, the biggest
privately held oil company on the planet.

216
00:15:25,633 --> 00:15:29,720
Now, does it surprise you
that Vera had a friend like that?

217
00:15:29,804 --> 00:15:31,806
Nothing surprises me anymore.

218
00:15:33,599 --> 00:15:35,101
You know what surprises me?

219
00:15:40,481 --> 00:15:42,525
This woman you say you spoke to.

220
00:15:43,651 --> 00:15:45,945
Here's security footage
of the alley you were in.

221
00:15:46,529 --> 00:15:47,530
There you are.

222
00:15:48,281 --> 00:15:49,407
All alone,

223
00:15:50,450 --> 00:15:51,701
talking to no one.

224
00:15:51,784 --> 00:15:53,828
No. No, she was there.

225
00:15:53,911 --> 00:15:56,414
-Doesn't look like it, does it?
-I swear to God she was there.

226
00:15:56,497 --> 00:15:57,790
I wasn't talking to myself.

227
00:15:57,874 --> 00:15:59,876
I believe you. Look.

228
00:16:03,629 --> 00:16:06,507
Your cigarette's unlit, and…

229
00:16:10,052 --> 00:16:11,554
Your cigarette's lit.

230
00:16:12,096 --> 00:16:14,765
You didn't light it yourself.
Your lighter doesn't work.

231
00:16:16,142 --> 00:16:20,313
Now, I don't know how, but someone
scrubbed her out of the footage.

232
00:16:20,813 --> 00:16:23,274
My team couldn't find
any trace of it being manipulated

233
00:16:23,357 --> 00:16:27,236
but we know it was,
which is fucking… pretty weird.

234
00:16:28,321 --> 00:16:32,116
Not as weird as the stars
turning on and off, but weird.

235
00:16:33,075 --> 00:16:35,328
Why did they wanna shut down your lab?

236
00:16:36,245 --> 00:16:37,079
I don't know.

237
00:16:37,163 --> 00:16:39,332
Well, you must be someone important.

238
00:16:39,415 --> 00:16:40,291
I'm not important.

239
00:16:40,374 --> 00:16:42,960
Well, you just invented
the world's finest nanofiber,

240
00:16:43,044 --> 00:16:45,338
3,000 times finer than human hair,

241
00:16:45,421 --> 00:16:48,382
invisible as air,
as strong as steel, all that shit.

242
00:16:48,466 --> 00:16:49,675
All that shit.

243
00:16:49,759 --> 00:16:52,887
Well, it's obviously dangerous to someone.

244
00:16:52,970 --> 00:16:54,222
Competitor, maybe.

245
00:16:54,305 --> 00:16:57,183
Yeah, a competitor
who made the universe flicker.

246
00:16:59,810 --> 00:17:01,354
Were you close to Vera Ye?

247
00:17:05,191 --> 00:17:06,275
I used to be.

248
00:17:07,318 --> 00:17:09,111
Smartest person I've ever met.

249
00:17:10,780 --> 00:17:12,031
Then I think I disappointed her

250
00:17:12,114 --> 00:17:14,700
'cause I quit her course
and switched into applied science.

251
00:17:15,618 --> 00:17:17,787
Maybe that's why she killed herself.

252
00:17:19,622 --> 00:17:21,582
This countdown you saw,

253
00:17:23,292 --> 00:17:26,504
it disappeared as soon as
you stopped your work, right?

254
00:17:27,255 --> 00:17:28,965
Has anyone else seen it?

255
00:17:29,048 --> 00:17:29,924
They have.

256
00:17:30,007 --> 00:17:32,343
A cybernetics professor in New Delhi.

257
00:17:32,426 --> 00:17:35,721
An AI scientist at Boston Dynamics.

258
00:17:35,805 --> 00:17:37,974
A physicist in London just the other day.

259
00:17:38,057 --> 00:17:39,308
Couple of dozen more.

260
00:17:40,434 --> 00:17:41,769
What happened to them?

261
00:17:43,771 --> 00:17:44,981
They quit working.

262
00:17:45,064 --> 00:17:46,857
